00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:56,188
narrator: tiny motion sensors known as accelerometers    

4
00:00:56,324 --> 00:00:58,991
are at the heart of much of today's technology. 

5
00:00:59,027 --> 00:01:00,259
built into a smartphone,    

6
00:01:00,328 --> 00:01:02,795
for example, the sensor detects both movement     

7
00:01:02,864 --> 00:01:05,264
and the angle at which the phone
is being held         

8
00:01:05,399 --> 00:01:07,532
to trigger the rotation of the screen.         

9
00:01:07,569 --> 00:01:08,601
this little chip is      

10
00:01:08,736 --> 00:01:11,003
why a smartphone knows when it has moved.    

11
00:01:15,676 --> 00:01:17,476
these motion sensors are tiny, 

12
00:01:17,478 --> 00:01:20,246
but smart, because they can detect every move.     

13
00:01:22,617 --> 00:01:26,618
they start with silicon disks called wafers.         

14
00:01:26,654 --> 00:01:29,956
each wafer will be used to make
thousands of motion sensors.  

15
00:01:33,628 --> 00:01:36,362
a technician aligns the disks in a cassette,         

16
00:01:36,497 --> 00:01:39,198
using the flat part of each one
as a reference point.     

17
00:01:42,403 --> 00:01:44,036
once properly aligned,     

18
00:01:44,105 --> 00:01:46,772
a mechanism lowers the silicon wafers onto a carrier     

19
00:01:46,808 --> 00:01:50,009
made of quartz, which can withstand intense heat.    

20
00:01:52,413 --> 00:01:55,281
the technician loads the wafers
into the furnace.       

21
00:01:58,653 --> 00:02:02,387
inside, the 2,000-degree heat and steam cause an oxide    

22
00:02:02,423 --> 00:02:05,725
to form on the surface of each wafer.         

23
00:02:05,860 --> 00:02:07,960
it'll act as an electrical insulator.  

24
00:02:12,734 --> 00:02:16,401
then it goes into what's known as a sputter system.      

25
00:02:16,437 --> 00:02:19,472
here, inert gas ions bombard aluminum,       

26
00:02:19,607 --> 00:02:21,540
causing it to sputter onto the wafer         

27
00:02:21,609 --> 00:02:24,810
until an even layer accumulates.

28
00:02:24,945 --> 00:02:29,415
this aluminum layer will serve as a conductor of electricity. 

29
00:02:29,417 --> 00:02:32,084
the next machine deposits a light-sensitive chemical   

30
00:02:32,086 --> 00:02:33,819
onto the wafer.        

31
00:02:33,888 --> 00:02:35,287
the wafer spins,        

32
00:02:35,356 --> 00:02:38,224
allowing the chemical to flow evenly across the surface.   

33
00:02:40,695 --> 00:02:43,829
this all happens under the glow
of yellow light        

34
00:02:43,831 --> 00:02:46,599
to prevent the untimely activation of the chemical,  

35
00:02:46,668 --> 00:02:48,234
which reacts to bright light  

36
00:02:48,236 --> 00:02:50,803
just like an unexposed photographic negative would.  

37
00:02:56,711 --> 00:03:00,112
they're now ready for that bright light.     

38
00:03:00,114 --> 00:03:03,648
u.v. light beams through tiny patterns on a glass plate   

39
00:03:03,718 --> 00:03:06,452
to activate the light-sensitive chemical. 

40
00:03:06,587 --> 00:03:09,255
the patterns transfer to the wafer's surface,    

41
00:03:09,390 --> 00:03:12,224
forming an outline       
for thousands of motion sensors.

42
00:03:14,595 --> 00:03:17,529
another chemical then flows onto the silicon wafer  

43
00:03:17,565 --> 00:03:19,999
to further develop these miniscule images.    

44
00:03:26,541 --> 00:03:29,275
next, lasers locate the wafer's flat edge, 

45
00:03:29,410 --> 00:03:31,010
signaling a chuck       

46
00:03:31,145 --> 00:03:35,214
to spin into its proper position
for plasma etching.      

47
00:03:35,216 --> 00:03:39,084
the etching creates thousands of free-moving 3-d structures. 

48
00:03:39,087 --> 00:03:40,953
each one is a motion sensor.  

49
00:03:43,624 --> 00:03:44,957
after etching,         

50
00:03:44,959 --> 00:03:48,227
a sprayer blasts the surface with carbon dioxide.      

51
00:03:48,362 --> 00:03:50,696
it's the only way to clean it without damaging  

52
00:03:50,765 --> 00:03:52,298
the now-movable sensors.    

53
00:03:54,502 --> 00:03:55,700
at the next station,      

54
00:03:55,737 --> 00:03:59,505
a robotic arm flips the wafer into position. 

55
00:03:59,507 --> 00:04:02,842
a tray moves under the robot and places the wafer on it.  

56
00:04:06,647 --> 00:04:08,647
the tray retracts and loads the wafer      

57
00:04:08,783 --> 00:04:09,915
into a clamping system.    

58
00:04:15,523 --> 00:04:17,990
it then collects a second silicon wafer     

59
00:04:18,125 --> 00:04:21,527
and places it on the first one in the clamp. 

60
00:04:21,596 --> 00:04:24,196
the second wafer acts as a lid            

61
00:04:24,198 --> 00:04:27,065
to protect the individual sensors.    

62
00:04:27,101 --> 00:04:30,536
held in the clamp, a machine heat-seals the two wafers,   

63
00:04:30,671 --> 00:04:32,004
and the bond is complete.   

64
00:04:36,611 --> 00:04:41,213
next, a computerized saw cuts 
grooves into the top wafer only,

65
00:04:41,249 --> 00:04:45,417
while a steady stream of water keeps the dust down.      

66
00:04:45,419 --> 00:04:48,754
the saw exposes the aluminum layer on the bottom wafer,   

67
00:04:48,823 --> 00:04:50,822
something that will allow each sensor          

68
00:04:50,858 --> 00:04:52,758
to make an electrical connection.          

69
00:04:56,597 --> 00:05:00,065
a platform now moves the wafer a millimeter at a time     

70
00:05:00,168 --> 00:05:02,367
so that a probe can test each sensor      

71
00:05:02,436 --> 00:05:05,304
and confirm it performs correctly.     

72
00:05:05,373 --> 00:05:07,840
this continues until every sensor on the wafer

73
00:05:07,842 --> 00:05:09,141
has been tested.        

74
00:05:11,546 --> 00:05:13,178
from a plain silicon wafer   

75
00:05:13,247 --> 00:05:16,582
to a unit that contains thousands of motion sensors -- 

76
00:05:16,717 --> 00:05:18,651
this process takes three weeks.

77
00:05:21,656 --> 00:05:23,255
after the individual sensors  

78
00:05:23,390 --> 00:05:25,657
have been cut and encased in plastic,    

79
00:05:25,693 --> 00:05:28,126
they're ready for a final test.

80
00:05:28,196 --> 00:05:32,397
a robot loads each sensor into a test socket.      

81
00:05:32,466 --> 00:05:35,267
the socket both tests the sensor's performance    

82
00:05:35,303 --> 00:05:39,471
and programs it to customer specifications.  

83
00:05:39,540 --> 00:05:43,609
a robot packages the sensors for shipping.         

84
00:05:43,611 --> 00:05:45,744
and once installed in phones, tablets,      

85
00:05:45,746 --> 00:05:47,012
and computers,         

86
00:05:47,147 --> 00:05:49,782
these motion sensors will be ready for action.   

